to the editor in connecting the dots column sept 25 thomas l friedman is right on the mark if the richest nations gave farmers in developing nations the opportunity to compete fairly in world markets to support their families those farmers would have a chance to grow into middle class communities and have good reasons to build democratic institutions on the other hand by spending 300 billion in annual subsidies to politically powerful agricultural groups the rich nations shortsightedly undermine those third world farmers and cultivate an environment more likely to produce frustrated and humiliated young people the kind of fruit most attractive for terrorist recruiters mark s nadel arlington va sept 25 2003

